<a id="comment-9545"></a>
  <div class="comment">
    <h3 class="title"><a href="/powered-usb-hub-my-hotel-room-and-more#comment-9545" class="active">Hotel-provided USB hub == security nightmare</a></h3>    <div class="submitted">Submitted by Brent Chapman (not verified) on Mon, 2009-04-13 21:12.</div>
    <div class="content"><p>I shudder at the thought of the damage somebody malicious could do with a USB hub in hotel rooms.  There's no security designed in to USB; the assumption is, if you're connecting to a device via USB, it's "your" device and you trust it.  If a drive appears on the USB chain, you mount it.  If it's got an autoexec.bat (or equivalent), you run it.  You can set your system to be more distrustful of USB-connected devices, but that's not the default.  So, imagine a malicious USB hub with a virus-infected drive built in (or hidden between the desk and the wall)...</p>
</div>
    <div class="links">&raquo; <ul class="links"><li class="first last comment_reply"><a href="/comment/reply/917/9545" class="comment_reply">reply</a></li>
</ul></div>
  </div>
<div class="indented"><a id="comment-9551"></a>
  <div class="comment">
    <h3 class="title"><a href="/powered-usb-hub-my-hotel-room-and-more#comment-9551" class="active">There is this risk, true</a></h3>    <div class="submitted">Submitted by <a href="/user/brad" title="View user profile." rel="nofollow">brad</a> on Tue, 2009-04-14 09:17.</div>
    <div class="content"><p>Though of course it is better to run an OS that won&#8217;t execute code from a USB device plugged into it!</p>

<p>You may be right that you can&#8217;t actually use the hub to access devices.  It is still handy of course for recharging.  Though you make me realize that if you plug your PDA/phone into it, it could then suck the data out of your phone.   So there are downsides of having power and data on the same bus.  One could have charging cables that have no data bits, I suppose.</p>

<p>(Though not for my damned RAZR, which refuses to charge from ordinary USB unless you install drivers on the computer to command it to accept a charge, or use a custom USB cable with the data wires shorted.)</p>

<p>I have wished there was a way to trust a hotel keyboard, though there is not.  You can probably trust a hotel mouse as a mouse, but since it could pretend to be other things, such as a CD or keyboard, you may not be able to trust even that.</p>

<p>One thing I proposed is a rule that devices which let you plug in external keyboards don&#8217;t let you type passwords on the keyboards &#8212; only on the device itself.  If they see you typing on the external keyboard when a password box is open in the browser, they could beep loudly at you.  But it&#8217;s not enough.</p>
</div>
    <div class="links">&raquo; <ul class="links"><li class="first last comment_reply"><a href="/comment/reply/917/9551" class="comment_reply">reply</a></li>
